      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The previous formula I provided calculates the number of terms in the sequence, not the number of divisors.\n\nTo calculate the number of divisors of a number `i`, we can use a different approach. We can iterate up to the square root of `i` and count the number of divisors. This is because a larger factor of `i` must be a multiple of a smaller factor that has already been counted.\n\nHere's the optimized function:\n\n```python\nimport math\n\ndef solve_problem(n):\n    def count_divisors(i):\n        count = 0\n        for j in range(1, int(math.sqrt(i)) + 1):\n            if i % j == 0:\n                if i // j == j:\n                    count += 1\n                else:\n                    count += 2\n        return count\n\n    return sum(count_divisors(i) for i in range(1, n + 1))\n```\n\nThis function should be able to handle large inputs within the time limit. However, keep in mind that it's still not the most efficient algorithm for this problem, as it has a time complexity of O(n sqrt(n)). If you need to optimize further, you may want to consider using a more advanced",
